The Southern states in India are primarily Tamil Nadu (where Tamil is spoken and where I'm from, so vannakam! :)), Kerala (where Malayalam is spoken), Andhra Pradesh and the recently formed Telengana (where Telugu is spoken) and Karnataka (where Kannada is spoken). These are all in the peninsular region of India, on what is geographically called the Deccan plateau, and have quite a distinct cultural and linguistic history from the states further to the North. 

You're right, in that they stretch right from the Southern most tip (Kanyakumari in Tamil Nadu) right to up to roughly the midpoint of the country (where the peninsular region ends), but are still referred to collectively as the South.

